{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deftab720\deflang2057{\fonttbl{\f0\fswiss Arial;}{\f1\fswiss \fcharset0 Arial;}{\f2\fmodern Courier New;}{\f3\fmodern \fcharset0 Courier New;}}{\colortbl\red0\green0\blue0;\red0\green128\blue0;\red0\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}\pard \plain \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <NS 1>\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b TPJHotLabel.\plain\f1\fs22\cf3\b Caption\plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b 
\par \plain\f0\fs12\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 2>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 TPJHotLabel\plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 2>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2           \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 6>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 See also\plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 6>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2  \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </NS 1>\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Specifies a text string that that is displayed in the label\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 .
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 3>\plain\f2\fs18\cf2\b property\plain\f2\fs18\cf2  \plain\f3\fs18\cf2 Caption\plain\f2\fs18\cf2 : \plain\f3\fs18\cf2 TCaption\plain\f2\fs18\cf2 ;\plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 3>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2\b Description\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Use Caption to set the text displayed in the label. If the \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 4>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 CaptionIsURL\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 4>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  property is \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i True\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  then the Caption and \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 5>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 URL\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 5>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  properties are equivalent, i.e. asigning a value to one will also assign the other. This makes it easy to display the URL in the label itself. To display text on the label that is different to the to the URL make sure that the CaptionIsURL property is \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i False\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 .
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 For reasons of backward compatibilty with earlier versions of the component the default behaviour is for the Caption property to display the URL (i.e. CaptionIsURL is \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i True\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 ).
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Note that if the \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 7>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 ValidateURL\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 7>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  and CaptionIsURL properties are both \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i True\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  then any text assigned to the Caption property must be a valid URL or an exception will be raised.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 To underline a character in Caption, include an ampersand (&) before the character. This type of character is called an accelerator character. The user can then select any control referenced by the \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 8>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 FocusControl\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 8>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  property by pressing Alt while typing the underlined character. To display an ampersand character in the caption, use two ampersands (&&). If the \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 9>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 ShowAccelChar\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 9>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  property is False ampersands are displayed literally and do not indicate accelerator characters.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The default value of the Caption property is the default URL: \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i http://localhost/\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par }

