\par \plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b TPJHotLabel.\plain\f1\fs22\cf3\b Cursor\plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b 
\par \plain\f0\fs12\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 2>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 TPJHotLabel\plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 2>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2  \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </NS 1>\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Specifies the image used to represent the mouse pointer when it passes into the region covered by the control\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 .
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 3>\plain\f3\fs18\cf2\b property\plain\f3\fs18\cf2  Cursor\plain\f2\fs18\cf2 : \plain\f3\fs18\cf2 TCursor\plain\f2\fs18\cf2 ;\plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 3>\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par 
\par \plain\f0\fs18\cf2\b Description\plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Change the value of Cursor to provide feedback to the user about what action is appropriate when the mouse pointer enters the control.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The value of Cursor is the index of the cursor in the list of cursors maintained by the global variable, Screen. In addition to the built-in cursors provided by TScreen, applications can add custom cursors to the list. See the \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 4>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 inherited Cursor property\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 4>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  of TControl for further details.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The Cursor property of TPJHotLabel differs from the inherited property in that its default cursor is \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  rather than \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crDefault\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 .
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  is not provided as a built-in cursor in earlier versions of Delphi, so a custom cursor is included when the component is compiled with these early versions. In later versions of Delphi the built-in \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  cursor is used. The value assigned to \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  is different depending on whether the custom or built-in cursors are used. 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The differences between versions of Delphi are:
\par \plain\f1\fs12\cf2 
\par \pard \fi-2000 \li2000 \tx1200 \tx2000 \plain\f1\fs18\cf1\i \protect <KP 9><BD 5>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i Version\tab Cursor\tab Notes\plain\f1\fs18\cf1\i \protect </BD 5></KP 9>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Delphi 2 & 3\tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <BM 7>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 \tab Since the cursor is custom the \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  constant has a positive value ($630B) and so a number is displayed in the object inspector rather than "crHandPoint".
\par 
\par Delphi 4 up\tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <BM 8>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 \tab The cursor is built in to Delphi and therefore the \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  constant has a Delphi-defined negative value. It displays in the object inspector as "crHandPoint".
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <BD 10>\plain\f1\fs12\cf2  \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </BD 10>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \pard Note that earlier versions of the component used a custom cursor named \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHand\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 . For backward compatibility this constant is also defined and has the same value as \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i crHandPoint\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 , although the value of the constant has changed from earlier versions (from $000A to $630B).\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par }

