{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deftab720\deflang2057{\fonttbl{\f0\fswiss Arial;}{\f1\fswiss \fcharset0 Arial;}{\f2\fnil \fcharset0 Courier New;}}{\colortbl\red0\green0\blue0;\red0\green128\blue0;\red0\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;\red0\green0\blue128;\red255\green0\blue0;}\pard \plain \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect <NS 1>\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b Example\plain\f1\fs22\cf3\b  1\plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b :\plain\f1\fs22\cf3\b  Using Highlighting\plain\f0\fs22\cf3\b 
\par \plain\f0\fs8\cf2  \plain\f0\fs18\cf1 \protect </NS 1>\plain\f0\fs8\cf2 
\par 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 This example presents two possible designs for \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 6>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 TPJHotLabel\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 6>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  components that use text highlighting to indicate that the label is clickable.
\par \plain\f1\fs12\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\b Example 1\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 This example uses a change in text decoration to highlight the text of the label when the mouse passes over it. We set \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 7>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Font.\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 7>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Style to \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i [ ]\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  and \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 8>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 HighlightFont\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 8>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 .Style to \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\i [fsUnderline]\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  and make HighlightFont.Color the same as Font.Color. We use a colour that is different from the standard label font to indicate the label is clickable. The un-highlightedlabel will display with no text decoration and the label will be underlined when the mouse passes over it.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Start a new application and place a TPJHotLabel component on the form. Double click the form to create a FormCreate event handler and enter the following code:
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 2>\plain\f2\fs18\cf2 TPJHotLabel1.Font.Color := clBlue;
\par TPJHotLabel1.HighlightFont := TPJHotLabel1.Font.Color;
\par TPJHotLabel1.Font.Style := [];
\par TPJHotLabel1.HighlightFont.Style := [fsUnderline];
\par TPJHotLabel1.HighlightURL := True;\plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 2>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Run the application and move the mouse cursor over the control to see the highlighting, as follows:
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \pard \li400 \tx2000 \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 4>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Normal style:\tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf3 http://localhost/\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par Highlighted style:\tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf3\ul http://localhost/\plain\f1\fs18\cf1\ul \protect </KP 4>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \pard \plain\f1\fs12\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2\b Example 2\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The second example uses a colour change to provide the highlighting. The default values of the Font and HighlightFont properties will suffice for this example - unhighlighted text is navy blue and is underlined while the highlighted text is red and is also underlined
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Start a new application and drop a TPJHotLabel component on the form. Either use the property inspector to set the HighlightURL property to true or create a FormCreate event handler and enter the following line of code:
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 3>\plain\f2\fs18\cf2 TPJHotLabel1.HighlightURL := True;\plain\f2\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 3>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Again, run the application and move the mouse cursor over the control to see the highlighting.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \pard \li400 \tx2000 \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 5>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Normal style:\tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf4\ul http://localhost/\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par Highlighted style:\tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf5\ul http://localhost/\plain\f1\fs18\cf1\ul \protect </KP 5>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par }

